# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: english-channel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:english-channel/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The **1983 France – United Kingdom Maritime Boundary Convention** is a 1983 treaty between France and the United Kingdom which establishes the maritime boundary between French Polynesia and the British territory of the Pitcairn Islands.
[src:english-channel/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The treaty was signed in Paris on 25 October 1983.
[src:english-channel/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The text of the treaty sets out a boundary that is an equidistant line between the nearest islands of the two territories.
[src:english-channel/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The boundary is roughly north–south and consists of five straight-line maritime segments defined by six individual coordinate points.
[src:english-channel/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The convention came into force on 12 April 1984, after both states had ratified it.
[src:english-channel/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] In 1993, after the United Kingdom declared an Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ) around the Pitcairn Islands, the two states agreed that the boundary set out in the 1983 treaty should also be the boundary between the French and British EEZs in the South Pacific.
[src:english-channel/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The full name of the treaty is *Convention on Maritime Boundaries between the Government of the French Republic and the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland*.
[src:english-channel/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The **1993 United Kingdom–United States Maritime Boundary Treaties** are two treaties between the United Kingdom and the United States which established a maritime boundary between British territories and American territories in the Caribbean Sea.
[src:english-channel/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] Both treaties were signed in London on 5 November 1993.
[src:english-channel/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The first treaty delimits the boundary between the British territory of Anguilla and the United States Virgin Islands.
[src:english-channel/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The boundary is a simplified equidistant line that consists of a single maritime straight-line segment 1.34 nautical miles (2.48 km; 1.54 mi) long.
[src:english-channel/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] It is defined by a straight line connecting two individual coordinate points.
[src:english-channel/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The full name of the treaty is *Treaty between the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland and the Government of the United States of America on the Delimitation in the Caribbean of a Maritime Boundary between the US Virgin Islands and Anguilla*.
[src:english-channel/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The second treaty delimits the boundary between the British Virgin Islands and the United States Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico.
[src:english-channel/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The boundary is a simplified equidistant line that runs in a south–south-east direction until it terminates at the tripoint of Anguilla.
[src:english-channel/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] It is far longer and more complicated than the Anguilla–U.S.
[src:english-channel/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] Virgin Islands boundary: it is about 200 nautical miles (370 km; 230 mi) long and consists of 49 straight-line segments defined by 50 individual coordinate points.
[src:english-channel/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The two treaties entered into force on 1 June 1995 after they had been ratified by both states.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The **1996 France – United Kingdom Maritime Delimitation Agreements** are two treaties between France and the United Kingdom which establish a number of maritime boundary between French territories and British territories in the Caribbean Sea.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] Both treaties were signed in London on 27 June 1996.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The two treaties entered into force on 30 January 1997 after they had been ratified by both states.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The first treaty delimits the boundary in the Anguilla Channel between the British territory of Anguilla and the French territories of Saint Martin and Saint Barthélemy.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The boundary is a simplified equidistant maritime line that runs in roughly an east–west direction.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] It consists of seven straight-line segments defined by eight individual coordinate points.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The western end of the border forms a tripoint with the Netherlands Antilles and the easternmost end of the border forms the tripoint with Antigua and Barbuda.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The full name of the treaty is *Agreement on maritime delimitation between the Government of the French Republic and the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland concerning Saint Martin and Saint Barthélemy, on one hand, and Anguilla on the other*.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] When the treaty was signed, Saint Martin and Saint Barthélemy were both part of the Guadeloupe overseas department of France.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] In 2007, Saint Martin and Saint Barthélemy became two separate overseas collectivities of France.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] As a result, the first treaty now defines only the Anguilla – Saint Martin maritime boundary.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] There is no maritime boundary between Anguilla and the separate collectivity of Saint Barthélemy.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The second treaty delimits the boundary between the British territory of Montserrat and the French territory of Guadeloupe.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The boundary is a simplified equidistant line that runs through the Guadeloupe Passage in roughly an east–west direction.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] It consists of four straight-line segments defined by five individual coordinate points.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The western end of the border forms the tripoint with Venezuela and the easternmost end of the border forms a tripoint with Antigua and Barbuda.
[src:english-channel/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The full name of the treaty is *Agreement on maritime delimitation between the Government of the French Republic and the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland concerning Guadeloupe and Montserrat*.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:english-channel/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] '**The Admiralty M-N Scheme'** (sometimes given as "**Project M-N**") was a World War I British plan to close the Strait of Dover in the English Channel to German U-boats, by means of a chain of either eight or twelve massive towers linked by anti-submarine booms and nets.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] Only two towers had been constructed before the Armistice with Germany caused the cancellation of the project.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] On 31 January 1917, it was announced to the German Reichstag that unrestricted submarine warfare would resume the next day, 1 February.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] The renewed U-boat campaign was initially a great success; nearly 500,000 tons of shipping being sunk in both February and March, and 860,000 tons in April, when Britain's reserve of wheat fell to 6 weeks' supply.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] The British Admiralty redoubled its efforts to find effective remedy.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] Attention turned to the Strait of Dover, which was used by U-boats based in Bruges in occupied Belgium, to gain fast access to the Atlantic trade routes and the busy Western Approaches.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] If it could be successfully closed to them, they would have to take the much longer "Northern Route" around the north of Scotland, and therefore be able to spend less time on patrol.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] Although this had been improved by use of the new Mark H2 mine from mid-1917, it was not initially very successful as there was no agreement on the depth at which the mines should be tethered.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] Until December 1917, only two U-boats had been destroyed by the barrage.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] Furthermore, the patrolling vessels were vulnerable to attack by German torpedo boats, as in the action of 26–27 October 1916, and the action of 20 April 1917.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] The Engineer-in-Chief to the Admiralty, Sir Alexander Gibb, devised a scheme of eight or twelve large concrete and steel towers, placed at intervals on the sea bed across the Dover Strait from Folkestone to Cap Gris Nez.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] Stretched between the towers would be improved anti-submarine nets; each tower would be equipped with two 4-inch guns, searchlights and hydrophone detection equipment.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] Gibb had worked with T G Menzies and Colonel William McLellan on a submarine detection system based on a galvanometer, which was also to be incorporated.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] There would be accommodation for 100 men on each of the towers.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] In June 1918, an advance party of Royal Engineers arrived at Southwick Green in Sussex where they established a camp.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] Construction of the first two towers was soon underway on the south side of Shoreham harbour nearby, each one consisting of an 80 feet (24 metres) high reinforced concrete raft made from interlocking cells, surmounted by a 1,000 ton steel column 90 feet (27 m) high and 40 feet (12 m) wide.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] The cost of the whole project was £12 million, an enormous sum for the time.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] The towers became visible for many miles around and were known locally as the "Shoreham mystery towers".
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] With the Armistice in November 1918, the whole project was cancelled; only Tower Number 1 was approaching completion.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] The Number One tower soon found an alternative use as a replacement for the Nab Rock lightship, 40 miles away off Bembridge in the Isle of Wight.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] On 12 September 1920, it was towed out of Shoreham harbour by five Admiralty tugs, watched by a crowd of thousands and was sunk on a sand spit next to the rock on the following day.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] The second tower remained at Shoreham until 1924 when it was demolished over a period of 6 months.
[src:english-channel/admiralty-m-n-scheme] Amongst the Royal Engineer officers involved in the construction of the towers was Guy Maunsell who later designed the Maunsell Sea Forts in World War II.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The **Adriatic Sea** (/ˌeɪdriˈætɪk/) is a body of water separating the Italian Peninsula from the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic is the northernmost arm of the Mediterranean Sea, extending from the Strait of Otranto (where it connects to the Ionian Sea) to the northwest and the Po Valley.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The countries with coasts on the Adriatic are Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Italy, Montenegro, and Slovenia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic contains more than 1,300 islands, mostly located along its eastern coast.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] It is divided into three basins, the northern being the shallowest and the southern being the deepest, with a maximum depth of 1,233 metres (4,045 ft).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The prevailing currents flow counterclockwise from the Strait of Otranto.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Tidal movements in the Adriatic are slight, although larger amplitudes occur occasionally.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's salinity is lower than the Mediterranean's because it collects a third of the fresh water flowing into the Mediterranean, acting as a dilution basin.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The surface water temperatures generally range from 30 °C (86 °F) in summer to 12 °C (54 °F) in winter, significantly moderating the Adriatic Basin's climate.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea sits on the Apulian or Adriatic Microplate.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Late Oligocene, the Italian Peninsula first formed, separating the Adriatic Basin from the rest of the Mediterranean.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The western coast is alluvial or terraced, while the eastern coast is highly indented with pronounced karstification.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] There are dozens of marine protected areas in the Adriatic, designed to protect the sea's habitats and biodiversity—more than 7,000 species are identified as native to the Adriatic, many of them endemic, rare and threatened ones.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's shores are populated by more than 3.5 million people; the largest cities are Bari, Venice, Trieste and Split.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Early settlements on the Adriatic shores were Etruscan, Illyrian, and Greek.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] By the 2nd century BC, the region was under Rome's control.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Middle Ages, the sea was controlled, to a varying extent, by a series of states—most notably the Byzantine Empire, the Croatian Kingdom, the Republic of Venice, the Habsburg monarchy and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Napoleonic Wars resulted in the Austrian Empire gaining control of most of the eastern Adriatic shore and the Po Valley, while the Kingdom of Italy gradually took control of the remaining Italian coast during the 19th century.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Following the collapse of Austria-Hungary in 1918, control of the eastern coast passed to Yugoslavia and Albania, which agreed on their maritime boundaries with Italy in 1975 and 1992 respectively.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] After Yugoslavia's dissolution during the 1990s, its four coastal successor states—Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Montenegro—continued to recognise the previous maritime border with Italy, but have disputed the borders between themselves.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Fisheries and tourism are significant sources of income along the Adriatic coast.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Maritime transport is also a significant branch of the area's economy—there are 19 seaports in the Adriatic that each handle more than a million tonnes of cargo per year.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The largest Adriatic seaport by annual cargo turnover is the Port of Trieste, while the Port of Split is the largest by passengers served per year.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The origins of the name *Adriatic* are linked to the Etruscan settlement of Adria, which probably derives its name from Illyrian *adur* 'water, sea'.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In classical antiquity, the sea was known as *Mare Adriaticum* (*Mare Hadriaticum*, also sometimes simplified to *Adria*) or, less frequently, as *Mare Superum* '[the] upper sea'.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The two terms were not synonymous, however.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] *Mare Adriaticum* generally corresponds to the Adriatic Sea's extent, spanning from the Gulf of Venice to the Strait of Otranto.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] That boundary became more consistently defined by Roman authors—early Greek sources place the boundary between the Adriatic and Ionian seas at various places ranging from adjacent to the Gulf of Venice to the southern tip of the Peloponnese, eastern shores of Sicily and western shores of Crete.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] *Mare Superum* on the other hand normally encompassed both the modern Adriatic Sea and the sea off the Apennine peninsula's southern coast, as far as the Strait of Sicily.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Another name used in the period was *Mare Dalmaticum*, applied to waters off the coast of Dalmatia or Illyricum.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] During the early modern period, the entire sea was also known as the **Gulf of Venice** (Italian: *golfo di Venezia*), although that name is now informally applied only to the northern area of the sea, from Maestra Point in the Po Delta to Cape Kamenjak on the Istrian Peninsula.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In Serbo-Croatian and Slovene, the sea is often referred to as simply *Jadran*.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea is a semi-enclosed sea, bordered in the southwest by the Apennine or Italian Peninsula, in the northwest by the Italian regions of Veneto and Friuli-Venezia Giulia, and in the northeast by Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Montenegro, and Albania—the Balkan peninsula.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the southeast, the Adriatic Sea connects to the Ionian Sea at the 72-kilometre (45 mi) wide Strait of Otranto.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] It extends 800 kilometres (500 mi) from the northwest to the southeast and is 200 kilometres (120 mi) wide.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] It covers 138,600 square kilometres (53,500 sq mi) and has a volume of 35,000 cubic kilometres (8,400 cu mi).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic extends northwest from 40° to 45°47' north, representing the Mediterranean's northernmost portion.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The sea is geographically divided into the Northern Adriatic, Central (or Middle) Adriatic, and Southern Adriatic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea drainage basin encompasses 235,000 square kilometres (91,000 sq mi), yielding a land–sea ratio of 1.8.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The drainage basin's mean elevation is 782 metres (2,566 ft) above sea level, with a mean slope of 12.1°.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Major rivers discharging into the Adriatic include the Po, Soča, Krka, Neretva, Drin, Buna, and Vjosë.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the late 19th century, Austria-Hungary established a geodetic network with an elevation benchmark using the average Adriatic Sea level at the Sartorio pier in Trieste, Italy.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The benchmark was subsequently retained by Austria, adopted by Yugoslavia, and retained by the states that emerged after its dissolution.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In 2016, Slovenia adopted a new elevation benchmark referring to the upgraded tide gauge station in the coastal town of Koper.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Alps, which also have a large meteorological impact on the Mediterranean, touch the Adriatic in the area around Trieste towards Duino and Barcola.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea contains more than 1,300 islands and islets, most along the Adriatic's eastern coast—especially in Croatia, with 1,246 counted.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The number includes islands, islets, and rocks of all sizes, including ones emerging at ebb tide only.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Croatian islands include the largest—Cres and Krk, each covering about the same area of 405.78 square kilometres (156.67 sq mi)—and the tallest—Brač, whose peak reaches 780 metres (2,560 ft) above sea level.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The islands of Cres and the adjacent Lošinj are separated only by a narrow navigable canal dug in the time of classical antiquity; the original single island was known to the Greeks as Apsyrtides.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Croatian islands include 47 permanently inhabited ones, the most populous among them being Krk, Korčula and Brač.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The islands along the Adriatic's western (Italian) coast are smaller and less numerous than those along the opposite coast; the best-known ones are the 117 islands on which the city of Venice is built.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The northern shore of the Greek island of Corfu also lies in the Adriatic Sea as defined by the IHO.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The IHO boundary places the Diapontia Islands (northwest of Corfu) in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea's average depth is 259.5 metres (851 ft), and its maximum depth is 1,233 metres (4,045 ft); however, the North Adriatic basin rarely exceeds a depth of 100 metres (330 ft).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The North Adriatic basin, extending between Venice and Trieste towards a line connecting Ancona and Zadar, is only 15 metres (49 ft) deep at its northwestern end; it gradually deepens towards the southeast.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] It is the largest Mediterranean shelf and is simultaneously a dilution basin and a site of bottom water formation.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Middle Adriatic basin is south of the Ancona–Zadar line, with the 270-metre (890 ft) deep Middle Adriatic Pit (also called the Pomo Depression or the Jabuka Pit).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The 170-metre (560 ft) deep Palagruža Sill is south of the Middle Adriatic Pit, separating it from the 1,200-metre (3,900 ft) deep South Adriatic Pit and the Middle Adriatic basin from the South Adriatic Basin.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Further on to the south, the sea floor rises to 780 metres (2,560 ft) to form the Otranto Sill at the boundary to the Ionian Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The South Adriatic Basin is similar in many respects to the Northern Ionian Sea, to which it is connected.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The coast's ruggedness is exacerbated by the Dinaric Alps' proximity to the coast, in contrast to the opposite (Italian) coast where the Apennine Mountains are further away from the shoreline.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The coastal water dynamics are determined by the asymmetric coasts and the inflow of the Mediterranean seawater through the Straits of Otranto and further on along the eastern coast.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The smooth Italian coast (with very few protrusions and no major islands) allows the Western Adriatic Current, which is composed of the relatively freshwater mass on the surface and the cold and dense water mass at the bottom, to flow smoothly.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The coastal currents on the opposite shore are far more complex owing to the jagged shoreline, several large islands and the proximity of the Dinaric Alps to the shore.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The last produces significant temperature variations between the sea and the hinterland, which leads to the creation of local jets.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The tidal movement is normally slight, usually remaining below 30 centimetres (12 in).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The amphidromic point is at the mid-width east of Ancona.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The normal tide levels are known to increase significantly in a conducive environment, leading to coastal flooding; this phenomenon is most famously known in Italy—especially Venice—as *acqua alta*.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Such tides can exceed normal levels by more than 140 centimetres (55 in), with the highest tide level of 194 centimetres (76 in) observed on 4 November 1966.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Such flooding is caused by a combination of factors, including the alignment of the Sun and Moon, meteorological factors such as sirocco related storm surges, and the basin's geometric shape (which amplifies or reduces the astronomical component).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Moreover, the Adriatic's long and narrow rectangular shape is the source of an oscillating water motion (French: *seiche*) along the basin's minor axis.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Finally, Venice is increasingly vulnerable to flooding due to coastal area soil subsidence.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Such unusually high tides resulting in flooding have also been observed elsewhere in the Adriatic Sea, and have been recorded in recent years in the towns of Koper, Zadar and Šibenik as well.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] It is estimated that the Adriatic's entire volume is exchanged through the Strait of Otranto in 3.4±0.4 years, a comparatively short period.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] (For instance, approximately 500 years are necessary to exchange all the Black Sea's water.) This short period is particularly important as the rivers flowing into the Adriatic discharge up to 5,700 cubic metres per second (200,000 cu ft/s).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] This rate of discharge amounts to 0.5% of the total Adriatic Sea volume, or a 1.3-metre (4 ft 3 in) layer of water each year.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The greatest portion of the discharge from any single river comes from the Po (28%), with an average discharge from it alone of 1,569 cubic metres per second (55,400 cu ft/s).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In terms of the annual total discharge into the entire Mediterranean Sea, the Po is ranked second, followed by the Neretva and Drin, which rank as third and fourth.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Another significant contributor of freshwater to the Adriatic is the submarine groundwater discharge through submarine springs (Croatian: *vrulja*); it is estimated to comprise 29% of the total water flux into the Adriatic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The submarine springs include thermal springs, discovered offshore near the town of Izola.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The thermal spring water is rich with hydrogen sulfide, has a temperature of 22 to 29.6 °C (71.6 to 85.3 °F), and has enabled the development of specific ecosystems.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The inflow of freshwater, representing a third of the freshwater volume flowing into the Mediterranean, makes the Adriatic a dilution basin for the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Middle and South Adriatic Gyres (SAG), are significant cyclonic circulation features, with the former being intermittent and the latter permanent.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The SAG measures 150 kilometres (93 miles) in diameter.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] It contributes to the flow of bottom water from the Adriatic to the Levantine Basin through the Ionian Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Through that process, the Adriatic Sea produces most of the East Mediterranean deep water.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's surface temperature usually ranges from 22 to 30 °C (72 to 86 °F) in the summer, or 12 to 14 °C (54 to 57 °F) in the winter, except along the western Adriatic coast's northern part, where it drops to 9 °C (48 °F) in the winter.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The distinct seasonal temperature variations, with a longitudinal gradient in the Northern and transversal gradient in the Middle and Southern Adriatic, are attributed to the continental characteristics of the Adriatic Sea: it is shallower and closer to land than are oceans.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] During particularly cold winters, sea ice may appear in the Adriatic's shallow coastal areas, especially in the Venetian Lagoon but also in isolated shallows as far south as Tisno (south of Zadar).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Southern Adriatic is about 8 to 10 °C (14 to 18 °F) warmer during the winter than the more northerly regions.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's salinity variation over the year is likewise distinct: it ranges between 38 and 39 PSUs, somewhat higher than the range of 32 to 37 PSUs for the open ocean.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The southern Adriatic is subjected to saltier water from the Levantine Basin.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification, the upper half of the Adriatic is classified as humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*), with wetter summers and colder and drier winters, and the southern Adriatic are classified as hot-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The air temperature can fluctuate by about 20 °C (36 °F) during a season.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The predominant winter winds are the bora and sirocco (called *jugo* along the eastern coast).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The bora is significantly conditioned by wind gaps in the Dinaric Alps bringing cold and dry continental air; it reaches peak speeds in the areas of Trieste, Senj, and Split, with gusts of up to 180 kilometres per hour (97 kn; 110 mph).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The sirocco brings humid and warm air, often carrying Saharan sand causing rain dust.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] On the Adriatic Sea's coasts and islands, there are numerous small settlements and a number of larger cities.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Among the largest are (counterclockwise) Trieste, Venice, Rimini, Ancona, Pescara and Bari in Italy; Vlorë and Durrës in Albania; Split, Zadar and Rijeka in Croatia; Koper in Slovenia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In total, more than 3.5 million people live on the Adriatic coasts.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] There are also some larger cities that are located very near the coast, such as the Italian cities of Ravenna and Lecce.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Venice, which was originally built on islands off the coast, is most at risk due to subsidence, but the threat is present in the Po delta as well.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The causes are a decrease in sedimentation rate due to loss of sediment behind dams, the deliberate excavation of sand for industrial purposes, agricultural use of water, and removal of ground water.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The sinking of Venice slowed after artesian wells were banned in the 1960s, but the city remains threatened by the *acqua alta* floods.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Recent studies have suggested that the city is no longer sinking, but a state of alert remains in place.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In May 2003, then-Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi inaugurated the MOSE project (Italian: *Modulo Sperimentale Elettromeccanico*), an experimental model for evaluating the performance of inflatable gates.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The project proposes laying a series of 79 inflatable pontoons across the sea bed at the three entrances to the Venetian Lagoon.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] When tides are predicted to rise above 110 centimetres (43 in), the pontoons will be filled with air and block the incoming water from the Adriatic Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] This engineering work was due to be completed by 2014, but as of November 2020 is expected to be completed in 2021.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] However, concern has been raised regarding the frequency of its use—while only necessary a few days a year, the worst-case sea level rise scenario between 2050 and 2100 would prompt deployment up to 187 days a year, essentially cutting off the Venetian Lagoon from the Adriatic Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Among other possible adverse effects, this can be expected to lower the lagoon's oxygen levels and trap pollution inside of the city.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Geophysical and geological information indicate that the Adriatic Sea and the Po Valley are associated with a tectonic microplate—identified as the Apulian or Adriatic Plate—that separated from the African Plate during the Mesozoic era.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] This separation began in the Middle and Late Triassic, when limestone began to be deposited in the area.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Between the Norian and Late Cretaceous, the Adriatic and Apulia Carbonate Platforms formed as a thick series of carbonate sediments (dolomites and limestones), up to 8,000 metres (26,000 ft) deep.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Remnants of the former are found in the Adriatic Sea, as well as in the southern Alps and the Dinaric Alps, and remnants of the latter are seen as the Gargano Promontory and the Maiella mountain.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Eocene and early Oligocene, the plate moved north and north-east, contributing to the Alpine orogeny (along with the African and Eurasian Plates' movements) via the tectonic uplift of the Dinarides and Alps.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Late Oligocene, the motion was reversed and the Apennine Mountains' orogeny took place.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] An unbroken zone of increased seismic activity borders the Adriatic Sea, with a belt of thrust faults generally oriented in the northeast–southwest direction on the east coast and the northeast–southwest normal faults in the Apennines, indicating an Adriatic counterclockwise rotation.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] An active 200-kilometre (120 mi) fault has been identified to the northwest of Dubrovnik, adding to the Dalmatian islands as the Eurasian Plate slides over the Adriatic microplate.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Furthermore, the fault causes the Apennine peninsula's southern tip to move towards the opposite shore by about 0.4 centimetres (0.16 in) per year.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] If this movement continues, the seafloor will be completely consumed and the Adriatic Sea closed off in 50–70 million years.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Northern Adriatic, the coast of the Gulf of Trieste and western Istria is gradually subsiding, having sunk about 1.5 metres (4 ft 11 in) in the past two thousand years.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Middle Adriatic Basin, there is evidence of Permian volcanism in the area of Komiža on the island of Vis and the volcanic islands of Jabuka and Brusnik.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Earthquakes have been observed in the region since the earliest historical records.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] A recent strong earthquake in the region was the 1979 Montenegro earthquake, measuring 7.0 on the Richter scale.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Historical earthquakes in the area include the 1627 Gargano peninsula and the 1667 Dubrovnik earthquakes, both followed by strong tsunamis.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the last 600 years, fifteen tsunamis have occurred in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] All types of seafloor sediments are found in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Northern Adriatic's comparatively shallow seabed is characterised by relict sand (from times when the water level was lower and the area was a sandy beach), while a muddy bed is typical at depths below 100 metres (330 ft).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Sediments deposited in the Adriatic Sea today generally come from the northwest coast, being carried by the Po, Reno, Adige, Brenta, Tagliamento, Piave and Soča rivers.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The volume of sediments carried from the eastern shore by the Rječina, Zrmanja, Krka, Cetina, Ombla, Dragonja, Mirna, Raša and Neretva rivers is negligible, because these sediments are mostly deposited at the river mouths.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's western shores are largely either alluvial or terraced, whereas the eastern shores are predominantly rocky, except for the southernmost part of the shore located in Albania that consists of sandy coves and rocky capes.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The eastern Adriatic shore's Croatian part is the most indented Mediterranean coastline.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Most of the eastern coast is characterised by a karst topography, developed from the Adriatic Carbonate Platform's exposure to weathering.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Karstification there largely began after the Dinarides' final uplift in the Oligocene and the Miocene, when carbonate deposits were exposed to atmospheric effects; this extended to the level of 120 metres (390 ft) below the present sea level, exposed during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] It is estimated that some karst formations are from earlier sea level drops, most notably the Messinian salinity crisis.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Similarly, karst developed in Apulia from the Apulian Carbonate Platform.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Rocks of the same type are found in Albania and on the western Adriatic coast.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] There are alternations of maritime and alluvial sediments occurring in the Po Valley, at the Adriatic's north-west coast, and as far west as Piacenza, dating to the Pleistocene as the sea advanced and receded over the valley.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] An advance began after the Last Glacial Maximum, which brought the Adriatic to a high point at about 5,500 years ago.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Since then, the Po delta has been prograding (expanding/extending).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The rate of coastal zone progradation between 1000 BC and 1200 AD was 4 metres (13 ft) per year.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the 12th century, the delta advanced at a rate of 25 metres (82 ft) per year.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the 17th century, the delta began to become a human-controlled environment, as the excavation of artificial channels started; the channels and new distributaries of the Po have been prograding at rates of 50 metres (160 ft) per year or more since then.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] There are more than 20 other rivers flowing into the Adriatic Sea in Italy alone, also forming alluvial coastlines, including the lagoons of Venice, Grado and Caorle.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] There are smaller eastern Adriatic alluvial coasts—in the deltas of the Dragonja, Buna and Neretva rivers.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea is a unique water body in respect of its overall biogeochemical physiognomy.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] It exports inorganic nutrients and imports particulate organic carbon and nitrogen through the Strait of Otranto—acting as a mineralization site.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The exchange of the substances is made more complex by bathymetry of the Adriatic Sea—75% of water flowing north through the strait recirculates at the Palagruža Sill and North Adriatic adds no more than 3–4% of water to the South Adriatic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] This is reflected in its biogeography and ecology, and particularly in the composition and properties of its ecosystems.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Its main biogeographic units are the Northern Adriatic, the Central Adriatic, and the Southern Adriatic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The unique nature of the Adriatic gives rise to an abundance of endemic flora and fauna.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Croatian National Biodiversity Strategy Action Plan identified more than 7,000 animal and plant species in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Central Adriatic is especially abundant in endemic plant species, with 535 identified species of green, brown and red algae.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Four out of five Mediterranean seagrass species are found in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The most common species are *Cymodocea nodosa* and *Zostera noltii*, while *Zostera marina* and *Posidonia oceanica* are comparatively rare.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] This circulation has significantly contributed to the biodiversity of the countries along the eastern Adriatic coast; the common bottlenose dolphin is frequent in the eastern coast's waters only, and the Croatian coast provides refuge for the critically endangered monk seal and sea turtles.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Recent studies revealed that cetaceans and other marine megafaunas, that were once thought to be vagrants to Adriatic Sea, migrate and live in the semi-closed sea on larger scales.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Largest of these live normally is the fin whale, and sperm whale, the largest of toothed whales also migrate but less common than fin whales, followed by Cuvier's beaked whales.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Basking sharks and manta rays are some of migrant species to the sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Historical presences of depleted or extinct species such as North Atlantic right whales (extinct or functionally extinct), Atlantic gray whales (extinct), and humpback whales have been speculated as well.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Tuna has been caught by the locals in the upper Adriatic for thousands of years.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The very large schools consisted mainly of little tunny and moved as far as the Gulf of Trieste.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] However, increasing fishing prevented the migration of large schools of fish to the north.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The last major tuna catch was made there in 1954 by the fishermen from Santa Croce, Contovello and Barcola.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Northern Adriatic in particular is rich in endemic fish fauna.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Around thirty species of fish are found in only one or two countries bordering the Adriatic Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] These are particularly due to or dependent upon the karst morphology of the coastal or submarine topography; this includes inhabiting subterranean habitats, karst rivers, and areas around freshwater springs.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] There are 45 known subspecies endemic to the Adriatic's coasts and islands.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Adriatic, there are at least 410 species and subspecies of fish, representing approximately 70% of Mediterranean taxa, with at least 7 species endemic to the Adriatic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Sixty-four known species are threatened with extinction, largely because of overfishing.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Only a small fraction of the fish found in the Adriatic are attributed to recent processes such as Lessepsian migration, and escape from mariculture.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The biodiversity of the Adriatic is relatively high, and several marine protected areas have been established by countries along its coasts.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In Italy, these are Miramare in the Gulf of Trieste (in the Northern Adriatic), Torre del Cerrano and Tremiti Islands in the Middle Adriatic basin and Torre Guaceto in southern Apulia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Miramare protected area was established in 1986 and covers 30 hectares (74 acres) of coast and 90 hectares (220 acres) of sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The area encompasses 1.8 kilometres (1.1 mi) of coastline near the Miramare promontory in the Gulf of Trieste.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Torre del Cerrano protected area was created in 2009, extending 3 nautical miles (5.6 km; 3.5 mi) into the sea and along 7 kilometres (4.3 mi) of coastline.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Various zones of the protected area cover 37 square kilometres (14 sq mi) of sea surface.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Tremiti Islands reserve has been protected since 1989, while the Tremiti islands themselves are part of the Gargano National Park.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Torre Guaceto protected area, located near Brindisi and Carovigno, covers a sea surface of 2,227 hectares (5,500 acres) and is adjacent to the Torre Guaceto State Reserve covering 1,114 hectares (2,750 acres) of coast and sharing an 8-kilometre (5.0 mi) coastline with the marine protected area.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Furthermore, there are 10 internationally important (Ramsar) wetland reserves in Italy located along the Adriatic coast.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Brijuni national park encompasses the 743.3-hectare (1,837-acre) archipelago itself and 2,651.7 hectares (6,552 acres) of surrounding sea; it became a national park in 1999.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Lim Canal is a 10-kilometre (6.2 mi) ria of the Pazinčica river.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Kornati national park was established in 1980; it covers approximately 220 square kilometres (85 sq mi), including 89 islands and islets.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The marine environment encompasses three-quarters of the total area, while the island shores' combined length equals 238 kilometres (148 mi).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Telašćica is a nature park established on Dugi Otok in 1988.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The park covers 69 kilometres (43 mi) of coastline, 22.95 square kilometres (8.86 sq mi) of land and 44.55 square kilometres (17.20 sq mi) of sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Bay of Mali Ston is located at the border of Croatia and Bosnia–Herzegovina, north of the Pelješac peninsula.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The marine protected area covers 48 square kilometres (19 sq mi).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Lastovo nature park was established in 2006, and it includes 44 islands and islets, 53 square kilometres (20 sq mi) of land and 143 square kilometres (55 sq mi) of sea surface.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Mljet national park was established in 1960, covering a 24-square-kilometre (9.3 sq mi) marine protection area.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In addition, there is a Ramsar wetland reserve in Croatia—the Neretva river's delta.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In Slovenia, the marine and coastal protected nature areas are the Sečovlje Salina Landscape Park, Strunjan Landscape Park, Škocjan Inlet Nature Reserve, and the Debeli Rtič, Cape Madona and Lakes in Fiesa natural monuments.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Sečovlje Salina Landscape Park was established in 1990, covers 721 hectares (1,780 acres), and includes four nature reserves.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In 1993, the area was designated a Ramsar site; it is also a site of international importance for waterbird species.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The 429-hectare (1,060-acre) Strunjan Landscape Park was established in 2004 and comprises two nature reserves.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] It includes a 4 kilometres (2.5 mi) long cliff, the northernmost Mediterranean salt field and the only Slovenian lagoon system.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] It is also the northernmost point of growth of some Mediterranean plant species.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Škocjan Inlet Nature Reserve was established in 1998 and covers 122 hectares (300 acres).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Debeli Rtič natural monument covers 24 hectares (59 acres), the Cape Madona natural monument covers 12 hectares (30 acres), and the Lakes in Fiesa natural monument, with the coastal lake as the only brackish lake in Slovenia, covers 2.1 hectares (5.2 acres).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In 2010, Albania established its first marine protection area, the Karaburun-Sazan National Marine Park at the Karaburun Peninsula where the Adriatic and Ionian Seas meet.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The park covers a total of 12,570 hectares (31,100 acres).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Two additional marine protection areas are planned in Albania: the Cape of Rodon (Albanian: *Kepi i Rodonit*) and Porto Palermo.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] In addition, Albania is home to two Ramsar wetland reserves: Karavasta Lagoon, and Butrint.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Neither Bosnia–Herzegovina nor Montenegro have or plan to establish any marine protection areas.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea ecosystem is threatened by excessive input of nutrients through drainage from agricultural land and wastewater flowing from cities; this includes both along its coast and from rivers draining into the sea—especially from the Po River.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Venice is often cited as an example of polluted coastal waters where shipping, transportation, farming, manufacturing and wastewater disposal contribute to polluting the sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] A further risk is presented by ballast water discharge by ships, especially tankers.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Still, since most of the cargo handled by the Adriatic ports, and virtually all liquid (tanker) cargo handled by the ports, is coming to—not coming from—the Adriatic Basin, the risk from ballast water (from tankers expelling ballast water then loading in the Adriatic) remains minimal.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] However, proposed export oil pipelines were objected to specifically because of this issue.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Oil spills are a major concern in terms of potential environmental impact and damage to tourism and fisheries.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] It is estimated that if a major oil spill happened, a million people would lose their livelihoods in Croatia alone.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] An additional risk is presented by oil refineries in the Po River basin where oil spills have occurred before, in addition to accidents occurring in the Adriatic already, so far with no significant environmental consequences.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Since 2006, Italy has been considering the construction of an offshore and an onshore LNG terminal in the Gulf of Trieste, as well as a pipeline, in the immediate vicinity of the Slovenian–Italian border.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] The Slovenian government and municipalities, the municipal council of Trieste, and non-governmental organisations have voiced concern over their environmental hazards, effect on transport and effect on tourism.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Another source of pollution of the Adriatic is solid waste.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Drifting waste—occasionally relatively large quantities of material, especially waste plastic—is transported northwest by the sirocco.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Air pollution in the Adriatic Basin is associated with the large industrial centres in the Po River valley and the large industrial cities along the coast.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Italy and Yugoslavia established a joint commission to protect the Adriatic Sea from pollution in 1977; the organization later changed with Slovenia, Croatia and Montenegro replacing Yugoslavia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] Future pollution hazards are addressed and pollution hotspots are assessed not only by nations in the basin but also through regional projects with World Bank support.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p01] 27 such hotspots have been determined as of 2011, 6 warranting an urgent response.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Settlements along the Adriatic dating to between 6100 and 5900 BC appear in Albania and Dalmatia on the eastern Adriatic coast, related to the Cardium pottery culture.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] During classical antiquity, Illyrians inhabited the eastern coast, and the western coast was inhabited by the peoples of Ancient Italy, mainly Etruscans, before the Roman Republic's rise.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Greek colonisation of the Adriatic dates back to the 7th and 6th centuries BC when the ancient cities of Epidamnos and Apollonia were founded.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Greeks soon expanded further north establishing several cities, including Ancona, Black Corcyra, Epidaurus, Issa, with trade established as far north as the Po River delta, where an emporium (trading station) was founded in Adria.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Roman economic and military influence in the region began to grow with the creation by 246 BC of a major naval base at Brundisium (now Brindisi), which was established to bar Carthaginian ships from the Adriatic during the Punic Wars.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] This led to conflict with the Illyrians, who lived in a collection of semi-Hellenized kingdoms that covered much of the Balkans and controlled the eastern shore of the sea, resulting in the Illyrian Wars from 229 to 168 BC.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The initial Roman intervention in 229 BC, motivated in part by a desire to suppress Illyrian piracy in the Adriatic, marked the first time that the Roman navy crossed that sea to launch a military campaign.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Those wars ended with the eastern shore becoming a province of the Roman Republic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] However, resistance to Roman rule continued sporadically and Rome did not completely consolidate control of the region until Augustus's general Tiberius put down the Great Illyrian Revolt, a bitter struggle waged from 6 to 9 AD.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Following the repression of the revolt the Roman province of Illyricum was split into Dalmatia and Pannonia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] During the Roman period, Brundisium, on the western shore, and Apollonia and Dyrrachium (originally called Epidamnos, now Durrës in Albania) on the eastern shore became important ports.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Brundisium was linked by the Via Appia road to the city of Rome, and Dyrrachium and Apollonia were both on the Via Egnatia, a road that by about 130 BC the Romans had extended eastward across the Balkans to Byzantium (later Constantinople, now Istanbul).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] This made the sea passage across the Adriatic between Brundisium and Dyrrachium (or Apollonia) a link in the primary route for travelers, trade, and troop movements, between Rome and the East.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] This route played a major role in some of the military operations that marked the end of the Roman Republic and the start of the imperial period.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Sulla used it during the First Mithridatic War.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Marc Antony and Octavian (later Augustus) crossed the Adriatic to Dyrrachium with their armies in their campaign against two of Caesar's assassins, Brutus and Cassius, that culminated in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Brundisium and Dyrrachium remained important ports well after the Roman period, but an earthquake in the 3rd century AD changed the path of a river causing Apollonia's harbor to silt up, and the city to decline.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Another city on the Italian coast of the Adriatic that increased in importance during the Roman era was Ravenna.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] During the reign of Augustus, it became a major naval base as part of his program to re-organize the Roman navy to better protect commerce in the Mediterranean.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] During the 4th century AD the emperors of the Western Roman Empire had moved their official residence north from Rome to Mediolanum (now Milan) in order to be better able to control the military frontier with the Germanic tribes.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 402 AD, during a period of repeated Germanic invasions of Italy, the capital was shifted to Ravenna because nearby marshes made it more defensible, and the Adriatic provided an easy escape path by sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] When the Western Empire fell in 476 AD Ravenna became the capital of the Ostrogothic Kingdom of Italy.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In the Early Middle Ages, after the Roman Empire's decline, the Adriatic's coasts were ruled by Ostrogoths, Lombards and the Byzantine Empire.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Ostrogothic Kingdom ruled Italy following the fall of the Western Roman Empire in 476 AD.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] However, during the reign of Justinian the Byzantine Empire sent an army under the general Belisarius to regain control of Italy, resulting in the Gothic War (535–554).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Byzantines established the Exarchate of Ravenna and by 553 AD their viceroy (Exarch) ruled almost the entire Italian peninsula from that city.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 568 AD the Lombards invaded northern Italy, and over the course of the next century or so the importance of the Exarchate declined as the territory under Lombard control expanded and as the Byzantine outpost of Venice became increasingly independent.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 752 AD the Lombards overthrew the Exarchate, ending the influence of the Byzantine Empire on the western shore of the Adriatic for a few centuries.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Republic of Venice, one of the maritime republics, was founded during this period and went on to become a significant maritime power after receiving a Byzantine tax exemption in 1082.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The end of the period brought about the Holy Roman Empire's control over the Kingdom of Italy (which would last until the Peace of Westphalia in 1648), the establishment of an independent Kingdom of Croatia and the Byzantine Empire's return to the southern Apennine peninsula.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In addition, the Papal States were carved out in the area around Rome and central Italy in the 8th century.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In this period, the Republic of Venice began to expand its territory and influence.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1202, the Fourth Crusade was diverted to conquer Zadar at the behest of the Venetians—the first instance of a Crusader force attacking a Catholic city—before proceeding to sack Constantinople.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In the 13th century, Venice established itself as a leading maritime nation.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] During much of the 12th and 13th centuries, Venice and the Republic of Genoa were engaged in warfare culminating in the War of Chioggia, ousting the Genoese from the Adriatic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Still, the 1381 Treaty of Turin that ended the war required Venice to renounce claims to Dalmatia, after losing the territory to Hungary in 1358.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In the same year, the Republic of Ragusa was established in Dubrovnik as a city-state after it was freed from Venetian suzerainty.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Venice regained Dalmatia in 1409 and held it for nearly four hundred years, with the republic's apex of trading and military power in the first half of the 15th century.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] These defeats spelled the end of an independent Hungarian kingdom, and both Croatian and Hungarian nobility chose Ferdinand I of the House of Habsburg as their new ruler, bringing the Habsburg monarchy to the shore of the Adriatic Sea, where it would remain for nearly four hundred years.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Ottomans and Venetians fought a series of wars, but until the 17th century these were not fought in the Adriatic area.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Ottoman raids on the Adriatic coasts effectively ceased after the massive setback in the Battle of Lepanto in October 1571.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The 17th century's final territorial changes were caused by the Morean or Sixth Ottoman–Venetian War, when in 1699 Venice slightly enlarged its possessions in Dalmatia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1797, the Republic of Venice was abolished after the French conquest.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Venetian territory was then handed over to Austria and briefly ruled as part of the Archduchy of Austria.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The territory was turned back over to France after the Peace of Pressburg in 1805 when the territory in the Po valley became an integral part of the new Napoleonic Kingdom of Italy.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The new kingdom included the province of Romagna, thus removing the Papal State from the Adriatic coast; however, Trieste, Istria and Dalmatia were joined into a set of separate provinces of the French Empire: the Illyrian Provinces.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] These were created in 1809 through the Treaty of Schönbrunn; they represented the end of Venetian rule on the eastern Adriatic coast, as well as the end of the Republic of Ragusa.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic Sea was a minor theatre in the Napoleonic Wars; the Adriatic campaign of 1807–1814 involved the Royal Navy contesting the Adriatic's control by the combined navies of France, Italy and the Kingdom of Naples.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] During the campaign, the British navy occupied Vis and established its base there in Port St.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The campaign reached its climax in the 1811 Battle of Lissa, and ended with British and Austrian forces seizing the coastal cities on the eastern Adriatic coast from the French.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Days before the Battle of Waterloo, the Congress of Vienna awarded the Illyrian Provinces (spanning from the Gulf of Trieste to the Bay of Kotor) to Austria.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Congress of Vienna also created the Kingdom of Lombardy–Venetia which encompassed the city of Venice, the surrounding coast and a substantial hinterland, and was controlled by Austria.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In the Apennine peninsula's south, the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies was formed in 1816 by unifying the kingdoms of Naples and Sicily.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The process of Italian unification culminated in the Second Italian War of Independence, resulting in the Kingdom of Sardinia annexing all territories along the western Adriatic coast south of Venetia in 1860, and the 1861 establishment of the Kingdom of Italy in its place.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Kingdom of Italy expanded in 1866: it annexed Venetia, but its navy was defeated in the Adriatic near Vis.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Following the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867 and the Croatian–Hungarian Settlement of 1868, the control of much of the eastern Adriatic coast was redefined.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The cisleithanian (Austrian) part of Austria-Hungary spanned from the Austrian Littoral to the Bay of Kotor, with the exception of the Croatian Littoral mainland.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In the territory outside the Austrian Littoral, special status was given to Fiume (modern-day Rijeka) as a separate part of the Kingdom of Hungary.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The rest of the territory was made a part of the Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia, which in turn was also in the Transleithanian part of the dual monarchy.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic coastline controlled by the Ottoman Empire was reduced by the Congress of Berlin in 1878, through recognition of the independence of the Principality of Montenegro, which controlled the coast south of the Bay of Kotor to the Bojana River.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Ottoman Empire lost all territories along the Adriatic following the First Balkan War and consequent 1913 Treaty of London that established an independent Albania.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The World War I Adriatic Campaign was largely limited to blockade attempts by the Allies and the effort of the Central Powers to thwart the British, French and Italian moves.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Italy joined the Allies in April 1915 with the Treaty of London, which promised Italy the Austrian Littoral, northern Dalmatia, the port of Vlorë, most of the eastern Adriatic islands and Albania as a protectorate.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The treaty provided the basis for all the following divisions between Italy and Yugoslavia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1918, the Montenegrin national assembly voted to unite with the Kingdom of Serbia, giving the latter access to the Adriatic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Another short-lived, unrecognised state established in 1918 was the State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs, formed from parts of Austria-Hungary, comprising most of the former monarchy's Adriatic coastline.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Later that year, the Kingdom of Serbia and the State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs formed the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes—subsequently renamed Yugoslavia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The proponents of the new union in the Croatian parliament saw the move as a safeguard against Italian expansionism as stipulated in the Treaty of London.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The treaty was largely disregarded by Britain and France because of conflicting promises made to Serbia and a perceived lack of Italian contribution to the war effort outside Italy itself.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The 1919 Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye did transfer the Austrian Littoral and Istria to Italy but awarded Dalmatia to Yugoslavia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Following the war, a private force of demobilized Italian soldiers seized Rijeka and set up the Italian Regency of Carnaro—seen as a harbinger of Fascism—in order to force the recognition of Italian claims to the city.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] During World War II, the Adriatic saw only limited naval action, starting with the Italian invasion of Albania and the joint Axis invasion of Yugoslavia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The latter led to the annexation of a large part of Dalmatia and nearly all the eastern Adriatic islands by Italy and the establishment of two puppet states, the Independent State of Croatia and the Kingdom of Montenegro, which controlled the remainder of the former Yugoslav Adriatic coast.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1947, after the Armistice between Italy and Allied armed forces and the war's end, Italy (now a republic) and the Allies signed the Treaty of Peace with Italy.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The FTT was partitioned in 1954: Trieste itself and the area to the North of it were placed under Italian control, while the rest came under Yugoslav control.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] This arrangement was made permanent in the 1975 Treaty of Osimo.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] During the Cold War, the Adriatic Sea became the southernmost flank of the Iron Curtain as Italy joined NATO, while the Warsaw Pact established bases in Albania.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] After the fall of communism, Yugoslavia broke apart: Slovenia and Croatia declared independence in 1991, and Bosnia–Herzegovina followed in 1992, while Montenegro remained in a federation with Serbia, officially called Serbia and Montenegro.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The ensuing Croatian War of Independence included limited naval engagements and a blockade of Croatia's coast by the Yugoslav Navy, leading to the Battle of the Dalmatian channels and a later withdrawal of Yugoslav vessels.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Montenegro declared itself independent in 2006, effectively land-locking Serbia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The period also saw the Adriatic Sea as the theatre of several NATO operations, including the blockade of Yugoslavia, intervention in Bosnia and Herzegovina and the 1999 bombing of Yugoslavia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Italy and Yugoslavia defined their Adriatic continental shelf delimitation in 1968, with an additional agreement signed in 1975 on the Gulf of Trieste boundary, following the Treaty of Osimo.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The boundary agreed in 1968 extends 353 nautical miles (654 km; 406 mi) and consists of 43 points connected by straight lines or circular arc segments.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The additional boundary agreed upon in 1975 consists of 5 points, extending from an end point of the 1968 line.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] All successor states of former Yugoslavia accepted the agreements.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In the Adriatic's southernmost areas the border was not determined in order to avoid prejudicing the location of the tripoint with the Albanian continental shelf border, which remains undefined.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Before the breakup of Yugoslavia, Albania, Italy and Yugoslavia initially proclaimed 15-nautical-mile (28 km; 17 mi) territorial waters, subsequently reduced to international-standard 12 nautical miles (22 km; 14 mi) and all sides adopted baseline systems (mostly in the 1970s).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Albania and Italy determined their sea border in 1992 according to the equidistance principle.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Following Croatian EU membership, the Adriatic became an internal sea of the EU.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea defines the Adriatic Sea as an enclosed or semi-enclosed sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic Euroregion was established in Pula in 2006 to promote trans-regional and trans-national cooperation in the Adriatic Sea area and serve as an Adriatic framework to help resolve issues of regional importance.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In addition, the maritime boundary between Albania and Montenegro was not defined before the 1990s.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia and Slovenia started negotiations to define maritime borders in the Gulf of Piran in 1992 but failed to agree, resulting in a dispute.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Both countries also declared their economic zones, which partially overlap.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia's application to become an EU member state was initially suspended pending resolution of its border disputes with Slovenia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] These disputes with Slovenia were eventually settled with an agreement to accept the decision of an international arbitration commission set up via the UN, enabling Croatia to progress towards EU membership.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia is still not following the resolution of the international arbitration for the Gulf of Piran.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] A dispute over the gulf is still on going with the Croatians handing out fines to Slovenian fishermen that are following the agreed economic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Aside from the EU membership difficulty, even before its settling the dispute has caused no major practical problems.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The maritime boundary between Bosnia–Herzegovina and Croatia was formally settled in 1999, but a few issues are still in dispute—the Klek peninsula and two islets in the border area.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Croatia–Montenegro maritime boundary is disputed in the Bay of Kotor, at the Prevlaka peninsula.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] This dispute was exacerbated by the peninsula's occupation by the Yugoslav People's Army and later by the (Serbian–Montenegrin) FR Yugoslav Army, which in turn was replaced by a United Nations observer mission that lasted until 2002.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia took over the area with an agreement that allowed Montenegrin presence in the bay's Croatian waters, and the dispute has become far less contentious since Montenegro's independence in 2006.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic Sea fishery's production is distributed among countries in the basin.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2000, the nominal—on a live weight basis—total landings of all Adriatic fisheries reached 110,000 tonnes (108,000 long tons).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Overfishing is a recognised problem—450 species of fish live in the Adriatic Sea, including 120 species threatened by excessive commercial fishing, a problem exacerbated by pollution and global warming.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Overexploited species include common dentex, red scorpionfish, monkfish, John Dory, blue shark, spiny dogfish, mullet, red mullet, Norway lobster, as well as European hake, and sardines.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Turtles and common bottlenose dolphins are also being killed by fishing nets.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The depleted fish stock, and Croatia's Ecological and Fisheries Protection Zone (ZERP) contributed to accusations of overfishing exchanged between Italian and Croatian fishermen.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] ZERP was introduced in 2003, but its application to EU member states was suspended in 2004.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The depleted stocks of fish are being addressed through a new proposed EU fisheries policy that was scheduled to take effect in 2013, when Croatia acceded to the EU, and restore the stocks to sustainable levels by 2015.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest volume of fish harvesting was in Italy, where the total production volume in 2007 stood at 465,637 tonnes (458,283 long tons).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2003, 28.8% of Italian fisheries production volume was generated in the Northern and central Adriatic, and 24.5% in Apulia (from the Southern Adriatic and Ionian Sea).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Italian fisheries, including those operating outside the Adriatic, employed 60,700 in the primary sector, including aquaculture (which comprises 40% of the total fisheries production).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The total fisheries output's gross value in 2002 was $1.9 billion.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2007, Croatia's production in live weight reached 53,083 tonnes (52,245 long tons).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2006, the total Croatian fisheries production volume was 37,800 tonnes (37,200 long tons) of catch and 14,200 tonnes (14,000 long tons) from marine aquaculture.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatian fisheries employed approximately 20,000.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatian marine aquaculture production consisted of tuna (47.2%), oysters and mussels (28.2% combined) and bass and bream (24.6% combined).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2007, Albanian fisheries production amounted to 7,505 tonnes (7,386 long tons), including aquaculture production, which reached 1,970 tonnes (1,940 long tons) in 2006.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] At the same time, Slovenian fisheries produced a total of 2,500 tonnes (2,460 long tons) with 55% of the production volume originating in aquaculture, representing the highest ratio in the Adriatic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Finally, the Montenegrin fisheries production stood at 911 tonnes (897 long tons) in 2006, with only 11 tonnes coming from aquaculture.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2007, the fisheries production in Bosnia–Herzegovina reached volume of 9,625 and 2,463 tonnes (9,473 and 2,424 long tons) in Slovenia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The countries bordering the Adriatic Sea are significant tourist destinations.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest number of tourist overnight stays and the most numerous tourist accommodation facilities are recorded in Italy, especially in the Veneto region (around Venice).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Veneto is followed by the Emilia-Romagna region and by the Adriatic Croatian counties.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Croatian tourist facilities are further augmented by 21,000 nautical ports and moorings; nautical tourists are attracted to various types of marine protected areas.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] As of January 2012, the Blue Flag has been awarded to 103 Italian Adriatic beaches and 29 marinas, 116 Croatian beaches and 19 marinas, 7 Slovenian beaches and 2 marinas, and 16 Montenegrin beaches.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Adriatic tourism is a significant source of income for these countries, especially in Croatia and Montenegro where the tourism income generated along the Adriatic coast represents the bulk of such income.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The direct contribution of travel and tourism to Croatia's GDP stood at 5.1% in 2011, with the total industry contribution estimated at 12.8% of the national GDP.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] For Montenegro, the direct contribution of tourism to the national GDP is 8.1%, with the total contribution to the economy at 17.2% of Montenegrin GDP.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Tourism in Adriatic Croatia has recently exhibited greater growth than in the other regions around the Adriatic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] There are nineteen Adriatic Sea ports (in four different countries) that each handles more than a million tonnes of cargo per year.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest cargo ports among them are the Port of Trieste (the largest Adriatic cargo port in Italy), the Port of Venice, the Port of Ravenna, the Port of Koper (the largest Slovenian port), the Port of Rijeka (the largest Croatian cargo port), and the Port of Brindisi.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest passenger ports in the Adriatic are the Port of Split (the largest Croatian passenger port) and ports in Ancona (the largest Italian passenger seaport in the Adriatic).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest seaport in Montenegro is the Port of Bar.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2010, the Northern Adriatic seaports of Trieste, Venice, Ravenna, Koper and Rijeka founded the North Adriatic Ports Association to position themselves more favourably in the EU's transport systems.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The port of Trieste is of particular importance for Central Europe because this is where the Transalpine Pipeline begins, supplying 100 percent of southern Germany, 90 percent of Austria and 50 percent of the Czech Republic with crude oil.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Natural gas is produced through several projects, including a joint venture of the Eni and INA companies that operates two platforms—one is in Croatian waters and draws gas from six wells, and the other (which started operating in 2010) is located in Italian waters.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic gas fields were discovered in the 1970s, but their development commenced in 1996.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2008, INA produced 14.58 million BOE per day of gas.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] About 100 offshore platforms are located in the Emilia-Romagna region, along with 17 in the Northern Adriatic.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Eni estimated its concessions in the Adriatic Sea to hold at least 40,000,000,000 cubic metres (1.4×1012 cu ft) of natural gas, adding that they may even reach 100,000,000,000 cubic metres (3.5×1012 cu ft).
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] INA estimates, however, are 50% lower than those supplied by Eni.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Oil was discovered in the Northern Adriatic at a depth of approximately 5,400 metres (17,700 ft); the discovery was assessed as not viable because of its location, depth and quality.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] These gas and oil reserves are part of the Po basin Province of Northern Italy and the Northern Mediterranean Sea.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In the 2000s, investigation works aimed at discovering gas and oil reserves in the Middle and Southern Adriatic basins intensified, and by the decade's end, oil and natural gas reserves were discovered southeast of the Bari, Brindisi—Rovesti and Giove oil discoveries.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Surveys indicate reserves of 3 billion barrels of oil in place and 5.7×1010 cubic metres (2,000,000,000,000 cu ft) of gas in place.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] The discovery was followed by further surveys off the Croatian coast.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] In January 2012, INA commenced prospecting for oil off Dubrovnik, marking the resumption of oil exploration along the eastern Adriatic coast after surveys commenced in the late 1980s around the island of Brač were cancelled because of Yugoslavia's breakup and war in Croatia.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] Montenegro is also expected to look for oil off its coast.
[src:english-channel/adriatic-sea-p02] As of January 2012, only 200 exploration wells had been sunk off the Croatian coast, with all but 30 in the Northern Adriatic basin.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The **Aegean Sea** is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea between Europe and Asia.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] It is located between the Balkans and Anatolia, and covers an area of some 215,000 km2 (83,000 sq mi).
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] In the north, the Aegean is connected to the Marmara Sea, which in turn connects to the Black Sea, by the straits of the Dardanelles and the Bosphorus, respectively.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are located within the sea and some bound it on its southern periphery, including Crete and Rhodes.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The sea reaches a maximum depth of 2,639 m (8,658 ft) to the west of Karpathos.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Thracian Sea and the Sea of Crete are main subdivisions of the Aegean Sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands can be divided into several island groups, including the Dodecanese, the Cyclades, the Sporades, the Saronic islands and the North Aegean Islands, as well as Crete and its surrounding islands.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Dodecanese, located to the southeast, includes the islands of Rhodes, Kos, and Patmos; the islands of Delos and Naxos are within the Cyclades to the south of the sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Lesbos is part of the North Aegean Islands.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Euboea, the second-largest island in Greece, is located in the Aegean, despite being administered as part of Central Greece.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Nine out of twelve of the Administrative regions of Greece border the sea, along with the Turkish provinces of Edirne, Çanakkale, Balıkesir, İzmir, Aydın and Muğla to the east of the sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Various Turkish islands in the sea are Imbros, Tenedos, Cunda Island, and the Foça Islands.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea has been historically important, especially regarding the civilization of Ancient Greece, which inhabited the area around the coast of the Aegean and the Aegean islands.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands facilitated contact between the people of the area and between Europe and Asia.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Along with the Greeks, Thracians lived along the northern coasts.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Romans conquered the area under the Roman Empire, and later the Byzantine Empire held it against advances by the First Bulgarian Empire.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Fourth Crusade weakened Byzantine control of the area, and it was eventually conquered by the Ottoman Empire, with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onwards.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The rocks making up the floor of the Aegean are mainly limestone, though often greatly altered by volcanic activity that has convulsed the region in relatively recent geologic times.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Of particular interest are the richly colored sediments in the region of the islands of Santorini and Milos, in the south Aegean.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Notable cities on the Aegean coastline include Athens, Thessaloniki, Heraklion, Volos, Alexandroupolis and Kavala in Greece, and İzmir and Bodrum in Turkey.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Several issues concerning sovereignty within the Aegean Sea are disputed between Greece and Turkey.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Aegean dispute has had a large effect on Greece-Turkey relations since the 1970s.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Issues include the delimitation of territorial waters, national airspace, exclusive economic zones, and flight information regions.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Ancient Greek authors also called it the "Greek Sea".
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The sea was known in Latin as *Mare Aegaeum* while under the control of the Roman Empire.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Pliny the Elder write that the Romans used the terms "Macedonian" for the northern part near Macedonia and Thrace provinces, and "Grecian" for the part near Greece itself.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] In medieval Latin, the Aegean Sea was known as *Egeopelagus*, a form attested as late as 1419 in Venetian state papers (Ducatus Egeopelagi) and derived from the Greek αἰγαιοπέλαγος / αἰγαῖον πέλαγος.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The term *Arcipelago* also appears, for instance in a treaty on 30 June 1268 between the Venetians and the emperor Michael Palaeologus.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] This term subsequently gave rise to *Archipelago* (Greek: αρχιπέλαγος), which in many European languages originally referred specifically to the Aegean Sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The terms *Greek Archipelago* or *Grecian Archipelago* were also used.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Later, as archipelago came to be used increasingly as a generic term for island-studded seas, the terms Greek Archipelago or Grecian Archipelago continued to be used alongside the ancient name, Aegean Sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] In some South Slavic languages, the Aegean is called *White Sea* (Bulgarian: Бяло море, romanized: *Byalo more*; Macedonian: Бело море, romanized: *Belo more*; Serbian: *Belo more* / Бело море).
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Turkish name for the sea is *Ege Denizi*, which is derived from the Greek name, and *Adalar Denizi* meaning "Sea of Islands".
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] In the past, Turks also referred to it as the "White Sea", to differentiate it from the Black Sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea and covers about 214,000 square kilometres (83,000 sq mi) in area, measuring about 670 kilometres (420 mi) longitudinally and 390 kilometres (240 mi) latitudinal.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The sea's maximum depth is 2,639 metres (8,658 ft), located at a point west of Karpathos.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are found within its waters, with the following islands delimiting the sea on the south, generally from west to east: Kythera, Antikythera, Crete, Kasos, Karpathos and Rhodes.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Anatolian peninsula marks the eastern boundary of the sea, while the Greek mainland marks the west.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Several seas are contained within the Aegean Sea; the Thracian Sea is a section of the Aegean located to the north, the Icarian Sea to the east, the Myrtoan Sea to the west, while the Sea of Crete is the southern section.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Greek regions that border the sea, in alphabetical order, are Attica, Central Greece, Central Macedonia, Crete, Eastern Macedonia and Thrace, North Aegean, Peloponnese, South Aegean, and Thessaly.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The traditional Greek region of Macedonia also borders the sea, to the north.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Many of the Aegean islands or island chains, are geographical extensions of the mountains on the mainland.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] One chain extends across the sea to Chios, another extends across Euboea to Samos, and a third extends across the Peloponnese and Crete to Rhodes, dividing the Aegean from the Mediterranean.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is connected to the Sea of Marmara by the Dardanelles, also known from Classical Antiquity as the Hellespont.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles are located to the northeast of the sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] It ultimately connects with the Black Sea through the Bosporus strait, upon which lies the city of Istanbul.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles and the Bosporus are known as the Turkish Straits.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Aegean surface water circulates in a counterclockwise gyre, with hypersaline Mediterranean water moving northward along the west coast of Turkey, before being displaced by less dense Black Sea outflow.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The dense Mediterranean water sinks below the Black Sea inflow to a depth of 23–30 metres (75–98 ft), then flows through the Dardanelles Strait and into the Sea of Marmara at velocities of 5–15 cm/s (2–6 in/s).
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Black Sea outflow moves westward along the northern Aegean Sea, then flows southwards along the east coast of Greece.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The physical oceanography of the Aegean Sea is controlled mainly by the regional climate, the fresh water discharge from major rivers draining southeastern Europe, and the seasonal variations in the Black Sea surface water outflow through the Dardanelles Strait.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The climate of the Aegean Sea largely reflects the climate of Greece and Western Turkey, which is to say, predominantly Mediterranean.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] According to the Köppen climate classification, most of the Aegean is classified as Hot-summer Mediterranean (*Csa*), with hotter and drier summers along with milder and wetter winters.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] However, high temperatures during summers are generally not quite as high as those in arid or semiarid climates due to the presence of a large body of water.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] This is most predominant in the west and east coasts of the Aegean, and within the Aegean islands.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] In the north of the Aegean Sea, the climate is instead classified as Cold semi-arid *(BSk)*, which feature cooler summers than Hot-summer Mediterranean climates.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Etesian winds are a dominant weather influence in the Aegean Basin.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Numerous Greek and Turkish settlements are located along their mainland coast, as well as on towns on the Aegean islands.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The largest cities are Athens and Thessaloniki in Greece and İzmir in Turkey.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The most populated of the Aegean islands is Crete, followed by Euboea and Rhodes.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Greece has established several marine protected areas along its coasts.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] According to the Network of Managers of Marine Protected Areas in the Mediterranean (MedPAN), four Greek MPAs are participating in the Network.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] These include Alonnisos Marine Park, while the Missolonghi–Aitoliko Lagoons and the island of Zakynthos are not on the Aegean.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The current coastline dates back to about 4000 BC.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Before that time, at the peak of the last ice age (about 18,000 years ago) sea levels everywhere were 130 metres (430 ft) lower, and there were large well-watered coastal plains instead of much of the northern Aegean.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] When they were first occupied, the present-day islands including Milos with its important obsidian production were probably still connected to the mainland.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The present coastal arrangement appeared around 9,000 years ago, with post-ice age sea levels continuing to rise for another 3,000 years after that.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The subsequent Bronze Age civilizations of Greece and the Aegean Sea have given rise to the general term *Aegean civilization*.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] In ancient times, the sea was the birthplace of two ancient civilizations – the Minoans of Crete and the Mycenaeans of the Peloponnese.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Minoan civilization was a Bronze Age civilization on the island of Crete and other Aegean islands, flourishing from around 3000 to 1450 BC before a period of decline, finally ending at around 1100 BC.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] It represented the first advanced civilization in Europe, leaving behind massive building complexes, tools, stunning artwork, writing systems, and a massive network of trade.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Minoan period saw extensive trade between Crete, Aegean, and Mediterranean settlements, particularly the Near East.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The most notable Minoan palace is that of Knossos, followed by that of Phaistos.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Mycenaean Greeks arose on the mainland, becoming the first advanced civilization in mainland Greece, which lasted from approximately 1600 to 1100 BC.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] It is believed that the site of Mycenae, which sits close to the Aegean coast, was the center of Mycenaean civilization.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Mycenaeans introduced several innovations in the fields of engineering, architecture and military infrastructure, while trade over vast areas of the Mediterranean, including the Aegean, was essential for the Mycenaean economy.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Their syllabic script, the Linear B, offers the first written records of the Greek language and their religion already included several deities that can also be found in the Olympic Pantheon.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Mycenaean Greece was dominated by a warrior elite society and consisted of a network of palace-centered states that developed rigid hierarchical, political, social and economic systems.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] At the head of this society was the king, known as *wanax*.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The civilization of Mycenaean Greeks perished with the collapse of Bronze Age culture in the eastern Mediterranean, to be followed by the so-called Greek Dark Ages.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] It is undetermined what cause the collapse of the Mycenaeans.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] During the Greek Dark Ages, writing in the Linear B script ceased, vital trade links were lost, and towns and villages were abandoned.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Archaic period followed the Greek Dark Ages in the 8th century BC.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Greece became divided into small self-governing communities, and adopted the Phoenician alphabet, modifying it to create the Greek alphabet.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] By the 6th century BC several cities had emerged as dominant in Greek affairs: Athens, Sparta, Corinth, and Thebes, of which Athens, Sparta, and Corinth were closest to the Aegean Sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Each of them had brought the surrounding rural areas and smaller towns under their control, and Athens and Corinth had become major maritime and mercantile powers as well.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] In the 8th and 7th centuries BC many Greeks migrated to form colonies in Magna Graecia (Southern Italy and Sicily), Asia Minor and further afield.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea was the setting for one of the most pivotal naval engagements in history, when, on 20 September 480 B.C., the Athenian fleet gained a decisive victory over the Persian fleet of the Xerxes II of Persia at the Battle of Salamis.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Thus ending any further attempt of western expansion by the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea would later come to be under the control, albeit briefly, of the Kingdom of Macedonia.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Philip II and his son Alexander the Great led a series of conquests that led not only to the unification of the Greek mainland and the control of the Aegean Sea under his rule, but also the destruction of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] After Alexander the Great's death, his empire was divided among his generals.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Cassander became king of the Hellenistic kingdom of Macedon, which held territory along the western coast of the Aegean, roughly corresponding to modern-day Greece.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Kingdom of Lysimachus had control over the sea's eastern coast.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Greece had entered the Hellenistic period.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Macedonian Wars were a series of conflicts fought by the Roman Republic and its Greek allies in the eastern Mediterranean against several different major Greek kingdoms.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] They resulted in Roman control or influence over the eastern Mediterranean basin, including the Aegean, in addition to their hegemony in the western Mediterranean after the Punic Wars.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] During Roman rule, the land around the Aegean Sea fell under the provinces of Achaea, Macedonia, Thracia, Asia and Creta et Cyrenaica (island of Crete).
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The fall of the Western Roman Empire allowed its successor state, the Byzantine Empire, to continue Roman control over the Aegean Sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] However, their territory would later be threatened by the early Muslim conquests initiated by Muhammad in the 7th century.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Although the Rashidun Caliphate did not manage to obtain land along the coast of the Aegean Sea, its conquest of the Eastern Anatolian peninsula as well as Egypt, the Levant, and North Africa left the Byzantine Empire weakened.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Umayyad Caliphate expanded the territorial gains of the Rashidun Caliphate, conquering much of North Africa, and threatened the Byzantine Empire's control of Western Anatolia, where it meets the Aegean Sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] During the 820s, Crete was conquered by a group of Berbers Andalusians exiles led by Abu Hafs Umar al-Iqritishi, and it became an independent Islamic state.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Byzantine Empire launched a campaign that took most of the island back in 842 and 843 under Theoktistos, but the re-conquest was not completed and was soon reversed.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Later attempts by the Byzantine Empire to recover the island were without success.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] For the approximately 135 years of its existence, the emirate of Crete was one of the major foes of Byzantium.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Crete commanded the sea lanes of the Eastern Mediterranean and functioned as a forward base and haven for Muslim corsair fleets that ravaged the Byzantine-controlled shores of the Aegean Sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Crete returned to Byzantine rule under Nikephoros II Phokas, who launched a huge campaign against the Emirate of Crete in 960 to 961.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Meanwhile, the Bulgarian Empire threatened Byzantine control of Northern Greece and the Aegean coast to the south.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Under Presian and his successor Boris I, the Bulgarian Empire managed to obtain a small portion of the northern Aegean coast.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Simeon I of Bulgaria led Bulgaria to its greatest territorial expansion, and managed to conqueror much of the northern and western coasts of the Aegean.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Second Bulgarian Empire achieved similar success along, again, the northern and western coasts, under Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Seljuk Turks, under the Seljuk Empire, invaded the Byzantine Empire in 1068, from which they annexed almost all the territories of Anatolia, including the east coast of the Aegean Sea, during the reign of Alp Arslan, the second Sultan of the Seljuk Empire.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] After the death of his successor, Malik Shah I, the empire was divided, and Malik Shah was succeeded in Anatolia by Kilij Arslan I, who founded the Sultanate of Rum.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Byzantines yet again recaptured the eastern coast of the Aegean.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Venetians created the maritime state of the Duchy of the Archipelago, which included all the Cyclades except Mykonos and Tinos.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Empire of Nicaea, a Byzantine rump state, managed to affect the Recapture of Constantinople from the Latins in 1261 and defeat Epirus.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Byzantine successes were not to last; the Ottomans would conquer the area around the Aegean coast, but before their expansion the Byzantine Empire had already been weakened from internal conflict.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] By the late 14th century, the Byzantine Empire had lost all control of the coast of the Aegean Sea and could only exercise power around their capital, Constantinople.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire then gained control of all the Aegean coast with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onward.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] In the aftermath of the Balkan Wars (1912–1913) Greece expanded northwards along the coast, while Bulgaria gained access in the northernmost section of the sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until its dissolution following World War I, when it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] After the war, Greece gained control over the area around the northern coast of the Aegean, including the territory held by Bulgaria.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] By the 1920s, Greece and Turkey had about resumed their present-day borders.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] In the Italo-Turkish War of 1912, Italy captured the Dodecanese islands, and had occupied them since, reneging on the 1919 Venizelos–Tittoni agreement to cede them to Greece.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Greco-Italian War took place from October 1940 to April 1941 as part of the Balkans Campaign of World War II.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Italian war aim was to establish a Greek puppet state, which would permit the Italian annexation of the Sporades and Cyclades islands in the Aegean Sea, to be administered as a part of the Italian Aegean Islands.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The German invasion resulted in the Axis occupation of Greece.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The German troops evacuated Athens on 12 October 1944, and by the end of the month, they had withdrawn from mainland Greece.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Greece was then liberated by Allied troops.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Many of the islands in the Aegean have safe harbours and bays.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] In ancient times, navigation through the sea was easier than travelling across the rough terrain of the Greek mainland, and to some extent, the coastal areas of Anatolia.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Many of the islands are volcanic, and marble and iron are mined on other islands.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The larger islands have some fertile valleys and plains.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Of the main islands in the Aegean Sea, two belong to Turkey – Bozcaada (Tenedos) and Gökçeada (Imbros); the rest belong to Greece.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Between the two countries, there are political disputes over several aspects of political control over the Aegean space, including the size of territorial waters, air control and the delimitation of economic rights to the continental shelf.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] These issues are known as the Aegean dispute.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Multiple ports are located along the Greek and Turkish coasts of the Aegean Sea.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The port of Piraeus in Athens is the chief port in Greece, the largest passenger port in Europe and the third largest in the world, servicing about 20 million passengers annually.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] With a throughput of 1.4 million TEUs, Piraeus is placed among the top ten ports in container traffic in Europe and the top container port in the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Piraeus is also the commercial hub of Greek shipping.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Piraeus bi-annually acts as the focus for a major shipping convention, known as Posidonia, which attracts maritime industry professionals from all over the world.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Piraeus is currently Greece's third-busiest port in terms of tons of goods transported, behind Agioi Theodoroi and Thessaloniki.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The central port serves ferry routes to almost every island in the eastern portion of Greece, the island of Crete, the Cyclades, the Dodecanese, and much of the northern and the eastern Aegean Sea, while the western part of the port is used for cargo services.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] As of 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki was the second-largest container port in Greece after the port of Piraeus, making it one of the busiest ports in Greece.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] In 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki handled 14,373,245 tonnes of cargo and 222,824 TEU's.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Paloukia, on the island of Salamis, is a major passenger port.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Fish are Greece's second-largest agricultural export, and Greece has Europe's largest fishing fleet.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Fish captured include sardines, mackerel, grouper, grey mullets, sea bass, and seabream.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] There is a considerable difference between fish catches between the pelagic and demersal zones; with respect to pelagic fisheries, the catches from the northern, central and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated, respectively, by anchovy, horse mackerels, and boops.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] For demersal fisheries, the catches from the northern and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated by grey mullets and pickerel (*Spicara smaris*) respectively.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The industry has been impacted by the Great Recession.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Overfishing and habitat destruction is also a concern, threatening grouper, and seabream populations, resulting in perhaps a 50% decline of fish catch.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] To address these concerns, Greek fishermen have been offered a compensation by the government.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Although some species are defined as protected or threatened under EU legislation, several illegal species such as the molluscs *Pinna nobilis*, *Charonia tritonis* and *Lithophaga lithophaga*, can be bought in restaurants and fish markets around Greece.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands within the Aegean Sea are significant tourist destinations.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Tourism to the Aegean islands contributes a significant portion of tourism in Greece, especially since the second half of the 20th century.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] A total of five UNESCO World Heritage sites are located the Aegean Islands; these include the Monastery of Saint John the Theologian and the Cave of the Apocalypse on Patmos, the Pythagoreion and Heraion of Samos in Samos, the Nea Moni of Chios, the island of Delos, and the Medieval City of Rhodes.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Greece is one of the most visited countries in Europe and the world with over 33 million visitors in 2018, and the tourism industry around a quarter of Greece's Gross Domestic Product.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The islands of Santorini, Crete, Lesbos, Delos, and Mykonos are common tourist destinations.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] An estimated 2 million tourists visit Santorini annually.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] However, concerns relating to overtourism have arisen in recent years, such as issues of inadequate infrastructure and overcrowding.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Alongside Greece, Turkey has also been successful in developing resort areas and attracting large number of tourists, contributing to tourism in Turkey.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The phrase "Blue Cruise" refers to recreational voyages along the Turkish Riviera, including across the Aegean.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The ancient city of Troy, a World Heritage Site, is on the Turkish coast of the Aegean.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Greece and Turkey both take part in the Blue Flag beach certification programme of the Foundation for Environmental Education.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] The certification is awarded for beaches and marinas meeting strict quality standards including environmental protection, water quality, safety and services criteria.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] As of 2015, the Blue Flag has been awarded to 395 beaches and 9 marinas in Greece.
[src:english-channel/aegean-sea] Southern Aegean beaches on the Turkish coast include Muğla, with 102 beaches awarded with the blue flag, along with İzmir and Aydın, who have 49 and 30 beaches awarded respectively.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The **English Channel**, also known as **the Channel**, is an arm of the Atlantic Ocean that separates Southern England from northern France.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] It links to the southern part of the North Sea by the Strait of Dover at its northeastern end.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] It is the busiest shipping area in the world.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] It is about 560 kilometres (300 nautical miles; 350 statute miles) long and varies in width from 240 km (130 nmi; 150 mi) at its widest to 34 km (18 nmi; 21 mi) at its narrowest in the Strait of Dover.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] It is the smallest of the shallow seas around the continental shelf of Europe, covering an area of some 75,000 square kilometres (22,000 square nautical miles; 29,000 square miles).
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel aided the United Kingdom in becoming a naval superpower, serving as a natural defence against invasions, such as in the Napoleonic Wars and in the Second World War.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The northern (English) coast of the Channel is more populous than the southern (French) coast.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The major languages spoken in this region are English and French.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Roman sources named the Channel *Oceanus Britannicus* (or *Mare Britannicum*, meaning the Ocean, or the Sea, of the Britons or *Britannī*).
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Variations of this term were used by influential writers such as Ptolemy, and remained popular with British and continental authors well into the modern era.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Other Latin names for the sea include *Oceanus Gallicus* (the Gaulish Ocean) which was used by Isidore of Seville in the sixth century.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The term *British Sea* is still used by speakers of Cornish and Breton, with the sea known to them as *Mor Bretennek* and *Mor Breizh* respectively.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] While it is likely that these names derive from the Latin term, it is possible that they predate the arrival of the Romans in the area.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The modern Welsh is often given as *Môr Udd* (the Lord's or Prince's Sea); however, this name originally described both the Channel and the North Sea combined.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Anglo-Saxon texts make reference to the sea as *Sūð-sǣ* (South Sea), but this term fell out of favour, as later English authors followed the same conventions as their Latin and Norman contemporaries.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] One English name that did persist was the *Narrow Seas*, a collective term for the channel and North Sea.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] As England (followed by Great Britain and the United Kingdom) claimed sovereignty over the sea, a Royal Navy Admiral was appointed with maintaining duties in the two seas.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The office was maintained until 1822, when several European nations (including the United Kingdom) adopted a three-mile (4.8 km) limit to territorial waters.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The word *channel* was first recorded in Middle English in the 13th century and was borrowed from the Old French word *chanel* (a variant form of *chenel* 'canal').
[src:english-channel/english-channel] By the middle of the fifteenth century, an Italian map based on Ptolemy's description named the sea as *Britanicus Oceanus nunc Canalites Anglie* (Ocean of the Britons but now English Channel).
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The map is possibly the first recorded use of the term *English Channel* and the description suggests the name had recently been adopted.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In the sixteenth century, Dutch maps referred to the sea as the *Engelse Kanaal* (English Channel) and by the 1590s, William Shakespeare used the word *Channel* in his history plays of Henry VI, suggesting that by that time, the name was popularly understood by English people.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] By the eighteenth century, the name *English Channel* was in common usage in England.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Following the Acts of Union 1707, this was replaced in official maps and documents with *British Channel* or *British Sea* for much of the next century.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] However, the term English Channel remained popular and was finally in official usage by the nineteenth century.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The French name *la Manche* has been used since at least the 17th century.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The name is usually said to refer to the sleeve (*la manche*) shape of the Channel.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Folk etymology has derived it from a Celtic word meaning 'channel' that is also the source of the name for the Minch in Scotland, but this name is not attested before the 17th century, and French and British sources of that time are clear about its etymology.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The name in French has been directly adapted in other languages as either a calque, such as *Canale della Manica* in Italian or the *Ärmelkanal* in German, or a direct borrowing, such as *Canal de La Mancha* in Spanish.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Strait of Dover (French: *Pas de Calais*), at the Channel's eastern end, is its narrowest point, while its widest point lies between Lyme Bay and the Gulf of Saint Malo, near its midpoint.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Well on the continental shelf, it has an average depth of about 120 m (390 ft) at its widest; yet averages about 45 m (148 ft) between Dover and Calais, its notable sandbank hazard being Goodwin Sands.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Eastwards from there the adjoining North Sea reduces to about 26 m (85 ft) across the Broad Fourteens (14 fathoms) where it lies over the southern cusp of the former land bridge between East Anglia and the Low Countries.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The North Sea reaches much greater depths east of northern Britain.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel descends briefly to 180 m (590 ft) in the submerged valley of Hurd's Deep, 48 km (30 mi) west-northwest of Guernsey.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] There are several major islands in the Channel, the most notable being the Isle of Wight off the English coast, and the Channel Islands, British Crown Dependencies off the coast of France.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The coastline, particularly on the French shore, is deeply indented, with several small islands close to the coastline, including Chausey and Mont-Saint-Michel.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Cotentin Peninsula on the French coast juts out into the Channel, with the wide Bay of the Seine (French: *Baie de Seine*) to its east.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] On the English side there is a small parallel strait, the Solent, between the Isle of Wight and the mainland.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Celtic Sea is to the west of the Channel.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel acts as a funnel that amplifies the tidal range from less than a metre at sea in eastern places to more than 6 metres in the Channel Islands, the west coast of the Cotentin Peninsula and the north coast of Brittany in monthly spring tides.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The time difference of about six hours between high water at the eastern and western limits of the Channel is indicative of the tidal range being amplified further by resonance.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel does not experience, but its existence is necessary to explain the extent of North Sea storm surges, such as necessitate the Thames Barrier, Delta Works, Zuiderzee works (Afsluitdijk and other dams).
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The full English Channel connecting the North Sea to the Western Atlantic via the Strait of Dover is of geologically recent origin, having formed late in the Pleistocene period.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The English Channel first developed as an arm of the Atlantic Ocean during the Pliocene period (5.3-2.6 million years ago) as a result of differential tectonic uplift along pre-existing tectonic weaknesses during the Oligocene and Miocene periods.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] During this early period, the Channel did not connect to the North Sea, with Britain and Ireland remaining part of continental Europe, linked by an unbroken Weald–Artois anticline, a ridge running between the Dover and Calais regions.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] During Pleistocene glacial periods this ridge acted as a natural dam holding back a large freshwater pro-glacial lake in the Doggerland region, now submerged under the North Sea.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] During this period, the North Sea and almost all of the British Isles were covered by ice.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The lake was fed by meltwater from the Baltic and from the Caledonian and Scandinavian ice sheets that joined to the north, blocking its exit.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The sea level was about 120 m (390 ft) lower than it is today.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Then, between 450,000 and 180,000 years ago, at least two catastrophic glacial lake outburst floods breached the Weald–Artois anticline.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] These contributed to creating some of the deepest parts of the channel such as Hurd's Deep.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The first flood of 450,000 years ago would have lasted for several months, releasing as much as one million cubic metres of water per second.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The flood started with large but localised waterfalls over the ridge, which excavated depressions now known as the *Fosses Dangeard*.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The flow eroded the retaining ridge, causing the rock dam to fail and releasing lake water into the Atlantic.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] It left streamlined islands, longitudinal erosional grooves, and other features characteristic of catastrophic megaflood events, still present on the sea floor and now revealed by high-resolution sonar.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Through the scoured channel passed a river, the Channel River, which drained the combined Rhine and Thames westwards to the Atlantic.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The flooding destroyed the ridge that connected Britain to continental Europe, although a land connection across the southern North Sea would have existed intermittently at later times when periods of glaciation resulted in lowering of sea levels.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] During the Last Interglacial/Eemian (115–130,000 years ago) the connection between the North Sea and the English Channel was fully open as it is today, resulting in Britain being an island during this interval, before lowered sea levels reconnected it to the continent during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] From the end of the Last Glacial Period, to the beginning of the Holocene rising sea levels again resulted in the unimpeded connection between the North Sea and the English Channel resuming due to the sinking of Doggerland, with Britain again becoming an island.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] As a busy shipping lane, the Channel experiences environmental problems following accidents involving ships with toxic cargo and oil spills.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Indeed, over 40% of the UK incidents threatening pollution occur in or very near the Channel.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] One occurrence was the MSC *Napoli*, which on 18 January 2007 was beached with nearly 1700 tonnes of dangerous cargo in Lyme Bay, a protected World Heritage Site coastline.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The ship had been damaged and was en route to Portland Harbour.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The English Channel, despite being a busy shipping lane, remains in part a haven for wildlife.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Atlantic oceanic species are more common in the westernmost parts of the channel, particularly to the west of Start Point, Devon, but can sometimes be found further east towards Dorset and the Isle of Wight.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Seal sightings are becoming more common along the English Channel, with both grey seal and harbour seal recorded frequently.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel is thought to have prevented Neanderthals from colonising Britain during the Last Interglacial/Eemian, though they returned to Britain during the Last Glacial Period when sea levels were lower.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel has in historic times been both an easy entry for seafaring people and a key natural defence, halting invading armies while in conjunction with control of the North Sea allowing Britain to blockade the continent.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] For nearly a thousand years, the Channel also provided a link between the Celtic Britons and Armorica, with modern Brittany being founded by British settlers during the Migration Period.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In more peaceful times, the Channel served as a link joining shared cultures and political structures, particularly the huge Angevin Empire from 1135 to 1217.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The most significant failed invasion threats came when the Dutch and Belgian ports were held by a major continental power, e.g. from the Spanish Armada in 1588, Napoleon during the Napoleonic Wars, and Nazi Germany during World War II.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Channel naval battles include the Battle of the Downs (1639), Battle of Dover (1652), the Battle of Portland (1653) and the Battle of La Hougue (1692).
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In February 1684, ice formed on the sea in a belt 4.8 km (3.0 mi) wide off the coast of Kent and 3.2 km (2.0 mi) wide on the French side.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Remnants of a Mesolithic boatyard have been found on the Isle of Wight.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Wheat was traded across the Channel about 8,000 years ago.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Sophisticated social networks linked the Neolithic front in southern Europe to the Mesolithic peoples of northern Europe." The Ferriby Boats, Hanson Log Boats and the later Dover Bronze Age Boat could carry a substantial cross-Channel cargo.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Diodorus Siculus and Pliny both suggest trade between the rebel Celtic tribes of Armorica and Iron Age Britain flourished.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In 55 BC Julius Caesar invaded, claiming that the Britons had aided the Veneti against him the previous year.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] He was more successful in 54 BC, but Britain was not fully established as part of the Roman Empire until Aulus Plautius's 43 AD invasion.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] A brisk and regular trade began between ports in Roman Gaul and those in Britain.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] This traffic continued until the end of Roman rule in Britain in 410 AD, after which the early Anglo-Saxons left less clear historical records.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In the power vacuum left by the retreating Romans, the Germanic Angles, Saxons, and Jutes began the next great migration across the North Sea.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Having already been used as mercenaries in Britain by the Romans, many people from these tribes crossed during the Migration Period, conquering and perhaps displacing the native Celtic populations.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The attack on Lindisfarne in 793 is generally considered the beginning of the Viking Age.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] For the next 250 years the Scandinavian raiders of Norway, Sweden, and Denmark dominated the North Sea, raiding monasteries, homes, and towns along the coast and along the rivers that ran inland.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] According to the *Anglo-Saxon Chronicle* they began to settle in Britain in 851.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] They continued to settle in the British Isles and the continent until around 1050, with some raids recorded along the channel coast of England, including at Wareham, Portland, near Weymouth and along the river Teign in Devon.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The fiefdom of Normandy was created for the Viking leader Rollo (also known as Robert of Normandy).
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Rollo had besieged Paris but in 911 entered vassalage to the king of the West Franks Charles the Simple through the Treaty of St.-Claire-sur-Epte.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In exchange for his homage and fealty, Rollo legally gained the territory he and his Viking allies had previously conquered.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The name "Normandy" reflects Rollo's Viking (i.e.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The descendants of Rollo and his followers adopted the local Gallo-Romance language and intermarried with the area's inhabitants and became the Normans – a Norman French-speaking mixture of Scandinavians, Hiberno-Norse, Orcadians, Anglo-Danish, and indigenous Franks and Gauls.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Rollo's descendant William, Duke of Normandy, became king of England in 1066 in the Norman Conquest beginning with the Battle of Hastings, while retaining the fiefdom of Normandy for himself and his descendants.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In 1204, during the reign of King John, mainland Normandy was taken from England by France under Philip II, while insular Normandy (the Channel Islands) remained under English control.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In 1259, Henry III of England recognised the legality of French possession of mainland Normandy under the Treaty of Paris.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] His successors, however, often fought to regain control of mainland Normandy.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] With the rise of William the Conqueror, the North Sea and Channel began to lose some of their importance.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The new order oriented most of England and Scandinavia's trade south, toward the Mediterranean and the Orient.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Although the British surrendered claims to mainland Normandy and other French possessions in 1801, the monarch of the United Kingdom retains the title Duke of Normandy in respect to the Channel Islands.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel Islands (except for Chausey) are Crown Dependencies of the British Crown.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Thus the Loyal toast in the Channel Islands is *Le roi, notre Duc* ("The King, our Duke").
[src:english-channel/english-channel] French Normandy was occupied by English forces during the Hundred Years' War in 1346–1360 and again in 1415–1450.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] From the reign of Elizabeth I, English foreign policy concentrated on preventing invasion across the Channel by ensuring no major European power controlled the potential Dutch and Flemish invasion ports.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Over the centuries, the Royal Navy slowly grew to be the most powerful in the world.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The building of the British Empire was possible only because the Royal Navy eventually managed to exercise unquestioned control over the seas around Europe, especially the Channel and the North Sea.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] During the Seven Years' War, France attempted to launch an invasion of Britain.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Another significant challenge to British domination of the seas came during the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Battle of Trafalgar took place off the coast of Spain against a combined French and Spanish fleet and was won by Admiral Horatio Nelson, ending Napoleon's plans for a cross-Channel invasion and securing British dominance of the seas for over a century.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The exceptional strategic importance of the Channel as a tool for blockading was recognised by the First Sea Lord Admiral Fisher in the years before World War I.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Singapore, the Cape, Alexandria, Gibraltar, Dover." However, on 25 July 1909 Louis Blériot made the first Channel crossing from Calais to Dover in an aeroplane.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Blériot's crossing signalled a change in the function of the Channel as a barrier-moat for England against foreign enemies.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Because the *Kaiserliche Marine* surface fleet could not match the British Grand Fleet, the Germans developed submarine warfare, which was to become a far greater threat to Britain.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Dover Patrol, set up just before the war started, escorted cross-Channel troopships and prevented submarines from sailing in the Channel, obliging them to travel to the Atlantic via the much longer route around Scotland.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] On land, the German army attempted to capture French Channel ports in the Race to the Sea but although the trenches are often said to have stretched "from the frontier of Switzerland to the English Channel", they reached the coast at the North Sea.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Much of the British war effort in Flanders was a bloody but successful strategy to prevent the Germans reaching the Channel coast.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] At the outset of the war, an attempt was made to block the path of U-boats through the Dover Strait with naval minefields.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] By February 1915, this had been augmented by a 25 kilometres (16 mi) stretch of light steel netting called the Dover Barrage, which it was hoped would ensnare submerged submarines.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] After initial success, the Germans learned how to pass through the barrage, aided by the unreliability of British mines.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] On 31 January 1917, the Germans resumed unrestricted submarine warfare leading to dire Admiralty predictions that submarines would defeat Britain by November, the most dangerous situation Britain faced in either world war.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Battle of Passchendaele in 1917 was fought to reduce the threat by capturing the submarine bases on the Belgian coast, though it was the introduction of convoys and not capture of the bases that averted defeat.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In April 1918 the Dover Patrol carried out the Zeebrugge Raid against the U-boat bases.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] During 1917, the Dover Barrage was re-sited with improved mines and more effective nets, aided by regular patrols by small warships equipped with powerful searchlights.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] A German attack on these vessels resulted in the Battle of Dover Strait in 1917.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] A much more ambitious attempt to improve the barrage, by installing eight massive concrete towers across the strait was called the Admiralty M-N Scheme but only two towers were nearing completion at the end of the war and the project was abandoned.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The naval blockade in the Channel and North Sea was one of the decisive factors in the German defeat in 1918.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] During the Second World War, naval activity in the European theatre was primarily limited to the Atlantic.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] During the Battle of France in May 1940, the German forces succeeded in capturing both Boulogne and Calais, thereby threatening the line of retreat for the British Expeditionary Force.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] By a combination of hard fighting and German indecision, the port of Dunkirk was kept open allowing 338,000 Allied troops to be evacuated in Operation Dynamo.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] More than 11,000 were evacuated from Le Havre during Operation Cycle and a further 192,000 were evacuated from ports further down the coast in Operation Aerial in June 1940.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The early stages of the Battle of Britain featured German air attacks on Channel shipping and ports; despite these early successes against shipping the Germans did not win the air supremacy necessary for Operation Sealion, the projected cross-Channel invasion.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel subsequently became the stage for an intensive coastal war, featuring submarines, minesweepers, and Fast Attack Craft.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The narrow waters of the Channel were considered too dangerous for major warships until the Normandy Landings with the exception, for the German Kriegsmarine, of the Channel Dash (Operation Cerberus) in February 1942, and this required the support of the Luftwaffe in Operation Thunderbolt.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Dieppe was the site of an ill-fated Dieppe Raid by Canadian and British armed forces.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] More successful was the later Operation Overlord (D-Day), a massive invasion of German-occupied France by Allied troops.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Caen, Cherbourg, Carentan, Falaise and other Norman towns endured many casualties in the fight for the province, which continued until the closing of the so-called Falaise gap between Chambois and Montormel, then liberation of Le Havre.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel Islands were the only part of the British Commonwealth occupied by Germany (excepting the part of Egypt occupied by the Afrika Korps at the time of the Second Battle of El Alamein, which was a protectorate and not part of the Commonwealth).
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Royal Navy blockaded the islands from time to time, particularly following the liberation of mainland Normandy in 1944.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Intense negotiations resulted in some Red Cross humanitarian aid, but there was considerable hunger and privation during the occupation, particularly in the final months, when the population was close to starvation.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The German troops on the islands surrendered on 9 May 1945, a day after the final surrender in mainland Europe.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] There is significant public concern in the UK about illegal immigrants coming on small boats from France.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Since 2018, the English Channel has seen a major increase in the number of crossings.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The English Channel coast is far more densely populated on the English shore.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The two dominant cultures are English on the north shore of the Channel, French on the south.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] However, there are also a number of minority languages that are or were found on the shores and islands of the English Channel, which are listed here, with the Channel's name in the specific language following them.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Most other languages tend towards variants of the French and English forms, but notably Welsh has *Môr Udd*.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel has traffic on both the UK–Europe and North Sea–Atlantic routes, and is the world's busiest seaway, with over 500 ships per day.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Following an accident in January 1971 and a series of disastrous collisions with wreckage in February, the Dover TSS, the world's first radar-controlled traffic separation scheme, was set up by the International Maritime Organization.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The scheme mandates that vessels travelling north must use the French side, travelling south the English side.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] There is a separation zone between the two lanes.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In December 2002 the MV *Tricolor*, carrying £30m of luxury cars, sank 32 km (20 mi) northwest of Dunkirk after collision in fog with the container ship *Kariba*.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The cargo ship *Nicola* ran into the wreckage the next day.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The shore-based long-range traffic control system was updated in 2003 and there is a series of traffic separation schemes in operation.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Though the system is inherently incapable of reaching the levels of safety obtained from aviation systems such as the traffic collision avoidance system, it has reduced accidents to one or two per year.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The ships were maintaining a very precise automated course, one directly behind the other, rather than making use of the full width of the traffic lanes as a human navigator would.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The MAIB report makes it clear that the harbour controllers were informed of impending disaster by shore observers before the crew were themselves aware.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The village of Kingsand was evacuated for three days because of the risk of explosion, and the ship was stranded for 11 days.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Many travellers cross beneath the Channel using the Channel Tunnel, first proposed in the early 19th century and finally opened in 1994, connecting the UK and France by rail.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] It is now routine to travel between Paris or Brussels and London on the Eurostar train.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Cars, coaches and lorries are carried on Eurotunnel Shuttle trains between Folkestone and Calais.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The coastal resorts of the Channel, such as Brighton and Deauville, inaugurated an era of aristocratic tourism in the early 19th century.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Short trips across the Channel for leisure purposes are often referred to as Channel hopping.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Rampion Wind Farm is an offshore wind farm located in the Channel, off the coast of West Sussex.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Other offshore wind farms planned on the French side of the Channel.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] As one of the narrowest and most well-known international waterways lacking dangerous currents, the Channel has been the first objective of numerous innovative sea, air, and human powered crossing technologies.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Pre-historic people sailed from the mainland to England for millennia.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] At the end of the last Ice Age, lower sea levels even permitted walking across.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Pierre Andriel crossed the English Channel aboard the *Élise*, ex the Scottish p.s.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] "Margery" in March 1816, one of the earliest seagoing voyages by steam ship.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The paddle steamer *Defiance*, Captain William Wager, was the first steamer to cross the Channel to Holland, arriving there on 9 May 1816.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] On 10 June 1821, English-built paddle steamer *Rob Roy* was the first passenger ferry to cross channel.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The steamer was purchased subsequently by the French postal administration and renamed *Henri IV* and put into regular passenger service a year later.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] It was able to make the journey across the Straits of Dover in around three hours.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In June 1843, because of difficulties with Dover harbour, the South Eastern Railway company developed the Boulogne-sur-Mer-Folkestone route as an alternative to Calais-Dover.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The first ferry crossed under the command of Captain Hayward.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] In 1974 a Welsh coracle piloted by Bernard Thomas of Llechryd crossed the English Channel to France in 131⁄2 hours.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The journey was undertaken to demonstrate how the Bull Boats of the Mandan Indians of North Dakota could have been copied from coracles introduced by Prince Madog in the 12th century.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Mountbatten class hovercraft (MCH) entered commercial service in August 1968, initially between Dover and Boulogne but later also Ramsgate (Pegwell Bay) to Calais.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The journey time Dover to Boulogne was roughly 35 minutes, with six trips per day at peak times.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The first aircraft to cross the Channel was a balloon in 1785, piloted by Jean Pierre François Blanchard (France) and John Jeffries (US).
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Louis Blériot (France) piloted the first aeroplane to cross in 1909.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The first flying car to have crossed the English Channel is a Pégase designed by the French company Vaylon on 14 June 2017.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] It was piloted by a Franco-Italian pilot Bruno Vezzoli.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] This crossing was carried out as part of the first road and air trip from Paris to London in a flying car.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Pegase is a two-seater road-approved dune buggy and powered paraglider.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The take-off was at 8:03 a.m. from Ambleteuse in the North of France and landing was at East Studdal, near Dover.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The flight was completed in 1 hour and 15 minutes for a total distance covered of 72.5 km (45.0 mi), including 33.3 km (20.7 mi) over the English Channel at an altitude of 1,240 metres (4,070 ft) .
[src:english-channel/english-channel] On 12 June 1979, the first human-powered aircraft to cross the English Channel was the *Gossamer Albatross*, built by American aeronautical engineer Dr.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] MacCready's company AeroVironment, and piloted by Bryan Allen.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The 35.7 km (22.2 mi) crossing was completed in 2 hours and 49 minutes.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] On 4 August 2019, Frenchman Franky Zapata became the first person to cross the English Channel on a jet-powered Flyboard Air.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The board was powered by a kerosene-filled backpack.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Zapata made the 35.4 km (22.0 mi) journey in 22 minutes, having landed on a boat half-way across to refuel.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The sport of Channel swimming traces its origins to the latter part of the 19th century when Captain Matthew Webb made the first observed and unassisted swim across the Strait of Dover, swimming from England to France on 24–25 August 1875 in 21 hours 45 minutes.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Up to 1927, fewer than ten swimmers (including the first woman, Gertrude Ederle in 1926) had managed to successfully swim the English Channel, and many dubious claims had been made.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel Swimming Association (CSA) was founded to authenticate and ratify swimmers' claims to have swum the Channel and to verify crossing times.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The CSA was dissolved in 1999 and was succeeded by two separate organisations: CSA Ltd (CSA) and the Channel Swimming and Piloting Federation (CSPF), both observe and authenticate cross-Channel swims in the Strait of Dover.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The Channel Crossing Association was also set up to cater for unorthodox crossings.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The team with the most Channel swims to its credit is the Serpentine Swimming Club in London, followed by the international Sri Chinmoy Marathon Team.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] As of 2023, 1,881 people had completed 2,428 verified solo crossings under the rules of the CSA and the CSPF.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] This includes 24 two-way crossings and three three-way crossings.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] As the Channel has been the busiest ocean shipping lane in the world for some time, it is governed by International Law as described in *Unorthodox Crossing of the Dover Strait Traffic Separation Scheme*.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The fastest verified swim of the Channel was by the Australian Trent Grimsey on 8 September 2012, in 6 hours 55 minutes, beating a swim of 2007.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] The female record is held by Yvetta Hlavacova of Czechia, on 7 hours, 25 minutes on 5 August 2006.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Both records were from England to France.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] There may have been some unreported swims of the Channel, by people intent on entering Britain in circumvention of immigration controls.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] A failed attempt to cross the Channel by two Syrian refugees in October 2014 came to light when their bodies were discovered on the shores of the North Sea in Norway and the Netherlands.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] On 16 September 1965, two Amphicars crossed from Dover to Calais.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] PLUTO was a war-time fuel delivery project of "pipelines under the ocean" from England to France.
[src:english-channel/english-channel] Though plagued with technical difficulties during the Battle of Normandy, the pipelines delivered about 8% of the fuel requirements of the Allied forces between D-Day and VE-Day.
